\emph{The following proof is not valid for the purpose of this exam
question since it doesn't use induction, but it is of the level of this
course, so we add it here for completeness.}

Another proof can be obtained by simply playing with the formula that
sums consecutive integers, that is

\begin{align*}
1+2+3+4+5+6+\dots + k = \sum_{i=1}^k i = \frac{k(k+1)}{2}
\end{align*}

And we just use the fact that

\begin{align*}
1+3+5+\dots+(2n-1) &= \left( 1+2+3+ \ldots +(2n-1) + (2n) \right) \\
&\quad - (2 + 4 + 6 + \ldots + (2n))
\end{align*} Or if we use sum notations

\begin{align*}
\sum_{i=1}^n (2i-1) = \sum_{i=1}^{2n} i - \sum_{i=1}^n 2i
\end{align*} Now using
the formula above we obtain that

\begin{align*}
\sum_{i=1}^{2n} i = \frac{2n(2n+1)}{2} = n(2n+1) = 2n^2+n
\end{align*} and

\begin{align*}
\sum_{i=1}^n 2i = 2\sum_{i=1}^n i = 2\frac{n(n+1)}{2} = n(n+1) = n^2+n
\end{align*}
And so

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
1+3+5+\dots+(2n-1) = (2n^2+n) - (n^2+n)=n^2
\end{align*} which proves that it is a
perfect square.
